1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:03,300
Before we dive into how transformer models the work,

2

00:00:03,300  -->  00:00:05,800
we will cover the basics of NLP.

3

00:00:05,800  -->  00:00:08,980
NLP stands for natural language processing,

4

00:00:08,980  -->  00:00:12,220
which is a branch of AI that aims at

5

00:00:12,220  -->  00:00:16,720
understanding and communicating using human language.

6

00:00:16,720  -->  00:00:22,620
Transformers is of course a part of a much larger NLP field.

7

00:00:22,620  -->  00:00:28,480
Since transformers were not created in a vacuum to understand how they work,

8

00:00:28,480  -->  00:00:33,680
we would need to have some prior knowledge in the area of NLP.

9

00:00:33,760  -->  00:00:35,880
In the next few videos,

10

00:00:35,880  -->  00:00:39,920
we'll cover a few topics that include tokenization,

11

00:00:39,920  -->  00:00:42,960
which is a process of converting a text into

12

00:00:42,960  -->  00:00:48,020
smaller parts that machine learning model can process, embeddings,

13

00:00:48,020  -->  00:00:54,280
which is a way to represent words of a text as a multi-dimensional vectors,

14

00:00:54,280  -->  00:00:59,720
and we'll also look into some simpler models that preceded transformers.

15

00:00:59,720  -->  00:01:03,990
First, let's talk about how AI models can process text.

16

00:01:03,990  -->  00:01:07,560
All machine learning models work with numbers,

17

00:01:07,560  -->  00:01:11,540
so we need to convert a text into numbers first.

18

00:01:11,540  -->  00:01:15,940
If we have a text like this for a machine learning model to handle it,

19

00:01:15,940  -->  00:01:19,740
we first need to split it into individual chunks.

20

00:01:19,740  -->  00:01:27,030
For example, we can split it into individual awards and convert each award into a number.

21

00:01:27,030  -->  00:01:30,480
We need to do this consistently so that

22

00:01:30,480  -->  00:01:34,685
the same word is always converted into the same number.

23

00:01:34,685  -->  00:01:41,460
For example, we can decide that the word welcome is always represented as number 11,

24

00:01:41,460  -->  00:01:46,740
and that the word course is represented as number 45, and so on.

25

00:01:46,740  -->  00:01:49,580
These numbers are called token IDs,

26

00:01:49,580  -->  00:01:54,600
and this is what our models will work with instead of working with words.

27

00:01:54,600  -->  00:01:59,020
It doesn't matter what numbers were assigned to each word as

28

00:01:59,020  -->  00:02:03,645
long as the same word is always converted into the same number.

29

00:02:03,645  -->  00:02:05,950
If we have another sentence,

30

00:02:05,950  -->  00:02:10,190
the way we convert words into numbers should be consistent.

31

00:02:10,190  -->  00:02:14,190
The same words should be converted into the same IDs,

32

00:02:14,190  -->  00:02:18,290
like the word course is converted into number 45.

33

00:02:18,290  -->  00:02:21,350
In order for our model to process any sentence,

34

00:02:21,350  -->  00:02:24,250
we need to know the words we can encounter

35

00:02:24,250  -->  00:02:28,050
and decide what IDs we will assign to each one of them.

36

00:02:28,050  -->  00:02:29,650
To get the list of words,

37

00:02:29,650  -->  00:02:35,125
we need to get a large collection of text and find all distinct words in it.

38

00:02:35,125  -->  00:02:37,260
To demonstrate this process,

39

00:02:37,260  -->  00:02:40,080
I've shown here a small text sample,

40

00:02:40,080  -->  00:02:44,740
but in reality, we need to have a much larger set of text.

41

00:02:44,740  -->  00:02:51,520
We need to split this text into individual words and find all unique words in this text.

42

00:02:51,520  -->  00:02:55,545
Each unique word will get its own unique ID.

43

00:02:55,545  -->  00:02:58,320
This table is called a vocabulary,

44

00:02:58,320  -->  00:03:04,020
and we can now use it to convert a new input text into a sequence of IDs,

45

00:03:04,020  -->  00:03:07,275
our model would be able to process.

46

00:03:07,275  -->  00:03:10,770
Then if we want to process a new sentence,

47

00:03:10,770  -->  00:03:17,125
we need to split it into tokens and find a corresponding ID for each word.

48

00:03:17,125  -->  00:03:19,800
For example, the word large,

49

00:03:19,800  -->  00:03:24,875
has ID 1, the word on has ID 5, and so on.

50

00:03:24,875  -->  00:03:27,960
In practice to build a good vocabulary,

51

00:03:27,960  -->  00:03:30,340
we need to process a lot of text,

52

00:03:30,340  -->  00:03:33,520
like all Wikipedia articles, for example.

53

00:03:33,520  -->  00:03:37,460
This will give us a list of all English words,

54

00:03:37,460  -->  00:03:39,660
as well as misspelled words,

55

00:03:39,660  -->  00:03:42,040
any words that are rarely used,

56

00:03:42,040  -->  00:03:46,060
words in languages we don't intend to process, and so on.

57

00:03:46,060  -->  00:03:49,260
We would end up with an enormous vocabulary,

58

00:03:49,260  -->  00:03:55,770
so to handle it, we will limit our vocabulary to the list of most common words.

59

00:03:55,770  -->  00:04:01,290
Say we would only use the most common 100,000 words or so.

60

00:04:01,290  -->  00:04:05,150
The downside of this approach is that some input text

61

00:04:05,150  -->  00:04:09,130
might include words that are not in our vocabulary.

62

00:04:09,130  -->  00:04:13,470
It can be because we've limited our vocabulary size or

63

00:04:13,470  -->  00:04:18,855
because we simply didn't see a particular word when we were creating one.

64

00:04:18,855  -->  00:04:24,480
For example, if we don't have words from the physics domain in our vocabulary,

65

00:04:24,480  -->  00:04:28,785
our model might have issues processing a sentence like this.

66

00:04:28,785  -->  00:04:33,440
A common way to handle it is to replace unknown words with

67

00:04:33,440  -->  00:04:39,240
a special token that represents an unknown word with its own unique ID,

68

00:04:39,240  -->  00:04:43,080
and pass this as an input to our model.

69

00:04:43,080  -->  00:04:45,400
The downside of this is that

70

00:04:45,400  -->  00:04:50,955
an unknown token does not provide a lot of information for our model.

71

00:04:50,955  -->  00:04:56,210
Splitting an input text into words is not the only option.

72

00:04:56,210  -->  00:05:00,250
We can split an input text into individual characters.

73

00:05:00,250  -->  00:05:03,090
In this case, the process will be the same,

74

00:05:03,090  -->  00:05:06,150
but instead of building a vocabulary of words,

75

00:05:06,150  -->  00:05:08,910
we'll build a vocabulary of characters,

76

00:05:08,910  -->  00:05:11,690
and every character will have an ID,

77

00:05:11,690  -->  00:05:14,130
we will convert it into.

78

00:05:14,410  -->  00:05:17,270
Then when tokenizing a sentence,

79

00:05:17,270  -->  00:05:20,150
we will split it into individual characters,

80

00:05:20,150  -->  00:05:24,120
and each character is converted into its own ID.

81

00:05:24,120  -->  00:05:30,110
Character level tokenization is a simple and useful technique that we'll also use.

82

00:05:30,110  -->  00:05:34,870
One benefit of character level tokenization is that it will be able

83

00:05:34,870  -->  00:05:39,950
to handle new words because it just splits them into individual characters.

84

00:05:39,950  -->  00:05:44,970
However, the main downside is that each individual token is much

85

00:05:44,970  -->  00:05:50,690
less meaningful compared to a token in the world level tokenization process.

86

00:05:50,690  -->  00:05:55,795
The last approach we will look into is called a subword tokenization.

87

00:05:55,795  -->  00:05:59,930
In this case, the input vocabulary consists of full words,

88

00:05:59,930  -->  00:06:02,670
as well as chunks of words.

89

00:06:02,880  -->  00:06:05,800
For example, in this sentence,

90

00:06:05,800  -->  00:06:12,480
similar words like pairs or involves are individual tokens with their own IDs.

91

00:06:12,480  -->  00:06:16,880
While the word quantum is split into two tokens,

92

00:06:16,880  -->  00:06:19,380
each with its own ID.

93

00:06:19,380  -->  00:06:24,450
Using subword tokenization helps with handling unknown words.

94

00:06:24,450  -->  00:06:27,050
If our model finds an unknown word,

95

00:06:27,050  -->  00:06:31,810
it can still split it into multiple tokens and make sense out of it.

96

00:06:31,810  -->  00:06:37,090
This approach is used by real world LLMs, such as GPT.

97

00:06:37,090  -->  00:06:41,290
If you want to experiment with it and if you want to try how it works,

98

00:06:41,290  -->  00:06:43,970
you can use the tiktoken library,

99

00:06:43,970  -->  00:06:49,230
a library that GPT is using to tokenize input sentences.
